{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:02:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:02:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18036"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18036"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58808"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7213"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the cutaneous branches of the cervical plexus is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The supraclavicular nerves arise from C3 and C4","The lesser occipital nerve arises from C2 and C3","The great auricular nerve arises from C1 and C2","The transverse cervical nerve arises from C4 and C5","The cervical plexus does not provide sensory innervation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cervical plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the first four cervical nerves (C1-C4). The cutaneous branches of the cervical plexus include the lesser occipital nerve, great auricular nerve, transverse cervical nerve, and supraclavicular nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe supraclavicular nerves\u003C/strong\u003E arise from C3 and C4 and provide sensory innervation to the skin over the shoulder and clavicle. This is the correct statement regarding the cutaneous branches of the cervical plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe lesser occipital nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from C2 and provides sensory innervation to the skin of the scalp behind the ear. It does not arise from C2 and C3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe great auricular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from C2 and C3 and supplies the skin over the parotid gland and the area behind the ear. It does not arise from C1 and C2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe transverse cervical nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from C2 and C3 and supplies the skin over the anterior triangle of the neck. It does not arise from C4 and C5.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe cervical plexus does not provide sensory innervation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as it provides sensory innervation to various regions of the neck and shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cervical plexus is formed by the anterior rami of the first four cervical nerves (C1-C4).","The supraclavicular nerves arise from the cervical plexus and are responsible for sensory innervation to the skin over the shoulder and clavicle.","The cervical plexus provides both motor and sensory innervation to the neck and upper shoulder region."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58808"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18036"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58808"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T11:39:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T11:39:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73337"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and r